<taxonomicName authorityName="Temminck" authorityYear="1836" box="[1023,1155,457,480]" class="Aves" family="Timaliidae" genus="Timalia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Passeriformes" pageId="84" pageNumber="85" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="trichorrhos">
<emphasis box="[1023,1155,457,480]" italics="true" pageId="84" pageNumber="85">trichorrhos</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
came fromâ€” 
<collectingRegion box="[787,882,486,509]" country="Indonesia" name="Sumatera Utara" pageId="84" pageNumber="85">Sumatra</collectingRegion>
or Borneo. 
<bibRefCitation author="Dekker, R. W. R. J." pageId="84" pageNumber="85" pagination="1 - 142" refId="ref92826" refString="Dekker, R. W. R. J. 2003. Type specimens of birds in the National Museum of Natural History, Leiden. Part 2. Passerines: Eurylaimidae - Eopsaltriidae (Peters's sequence). Nationaal Natuurhistorisch Museum, Technical Bulletin 6: 1 - 142." type="journal article" year="2003">Dekker (2003: 50)</bibRefCitation>
discussed this possibility and noted that if an ongoing search for Sumatran type material available to Temminck is not found, â€˜â€˜then a Sumatran 
